Introduction and Overview

In this report, we explore the employee attrition dataset. This dataset contains employees who have either left a company or not as well as 37 different variables potentially relating to this. The steps and procedures taken for this analysis are detailed below. We start by looking at the most important factors for employee attrition and then any trends for different job roles. Finally, we create two prediction models, one classifier to predict attrition and one linear regression to predict monthly income.

Useful Links

  • GitHub: This link contains all of the data, R code, and power points.

  • Employee Attrition App: This link contains an R Shiny app that allows the user to explore the attrition rates of different job roles and education fields, as well as the monthly income.

  • Presentation of Results - YouTube: Video of the presentation of results of Employee Attrition analysis.

  • README.md: This page shows an introduction to the analysis we ran. It also includes a few details about the datasets provided.

  • Beers.csv

The results of a two sample t-test on the monthly income data.

## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  log(attrY$MonthlyIncome) and log(attrN$MonthlyIncome)
## t = -5.9707, df = 868, p-value = 0.000000003442
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.4748425 -0.2398918
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  8.237820  8.595187

There is evidence to suggest that the median income for workers who quit is lower than workers who did not quit (p-value<0.0000001)
